Kia ora Grant,

Thanks for your email and for proposing to bring stakeholders together. As =
you=E2=80=99ve said, you =E2=80=9C will gather the supporting information=
=E2=80=A6 and provide that=E2=80=A6 well ahead of [any] site meeting,=E2=80=
=9D and you=E2=80=99ll send an agenda based on my email.

Could you please first send your written responses to my questions and the =
supporting documents (reports, scope, raw notes/photo logs from prior atten=
dances, and the test-led plan with methods, thresholds, labs and pass/fail =
criteria)? Once I have those, I can identify the appropriate experts to att=
end.



Given I rely on third-party availability, please plan on 1=E2=80=932 weeks=
=E2=80=99 notice after I receive your written responses and the agenda. I=
=E2=80=99m very happy to meet then.

To avoid further email back-and-forth, please also include:



  *   AC2213/Council path (consent or written exemption) and confirmation o=
f CPEng engagement. The repairs qualify to be completed under schedule 1 as=
 per extract following which is taken from the ASURNZ response provided fur=
ther below. There is no requirement to provide CPEng engagement. However To=
wer is prepared

Regarding the provisions of s.112 of the Building Act 2004, these do not ap=
ply to the repair of this dwelling as none of the required building work re=
quires a building consent.  Similarly, the practice note from Auckland Coun=
cil does not apply, and in any case is not a regulatory or legislative requ=
irement.  Note that the defining legislation is the Building Act 2004 (the =
Act).  The Act overrides any policy of a building consent authority.  The p=
rovisions of the Act make clear that a building consent is not required for=
 the proposed repairs to this dwelling.


  *   Hold-points and clearances (roof/eaves intrusives, cavities, corrosio=
n/pH-chloride, IAQ, whole-installation electrical to AS/NZS 3000, HVAC/gas =
hygiene);
Chemical Contamination Testing
Hold points can be established for swab testing for the potential chemical =
contamination that you have advised us of after we have completed base test=
s. To assist in establishing this we must first obtain a schedule of the ch=
emicals which were present during the fire, and have it confirmed where the=
y were located so appropriate testing can be undertaken. We would appoint a=
 Forensic Scientist to undertake testing of the current environment and the=
n report their findings to all parties to consider. We can not define hold-=
points until we understand the extent of the chemical contamination and whe=
re it exists.
Roof & Eaves
There is no need for invasive assessment on these components as they are re=
adily accessible and visible both externally and internally.
Cavities
We have completed invasive cavity inspection with your knowledge to determi=
ne the condition of the external wall cavities. We can review these during =
the site meeting.

  *   Any directions provided to ASURNZ. These will be sent you under the p=
rivacy request which claims is processing now.

Once received I=E2=80=99ll revert with attendee names and propose meeting d=
ates within the 1=E2=80=932 week window.


