Hi Grant, I have read through the concerns raised by your customer in the e=
mail below. I think it would be useful for us to clarify the involvement of=
 ASURNZ, our independence to Tower Insurance, our experience, and our appro=
ach to determining

Hi Grant,

I have read through the concerns raised by your customer in the email below=
.  I think it would be useful for us to clarify the involvement of ASURNZ, =
our independence to Tower Insurance, our experience, and our approach to de=
termining remediation required for damage caused by fire, heat, chemicals, =
and smoke resulting from fire related events.

Fairness and participation
ASURNZ operates as third-party provider specialising in damage assessment a=
nd remediation, building product and building system compliance, and legisl=
ative and regulatory requirements for building related matters.  In these m=
atters we also provide expert witness services to the Courts.  Our customer=
s include private building owners (residential, commercial, and industrial)=
, insurers, building consent authorities (including Auckland Council), and =
building product manufacturers. As such we provide a service that is indepe=
ndent and impartial of Tower Insurance.
Details from our site inspection, including relevant photo schedules are pr=
ovided in our reporting, however we understand that homeowners will often h=
ave property specific questions. We are happy to meet with your customer to=
 go over our findings, and to listen to and consider their concerns.

Fire chemistry & severity
ASURNZ has extensive experience in the assessment and remediation of fire/s=
moke damaged buildings.  In all building fires there is risk that materials=
 affected by fire can contribute to or cause corrosion from airborne means =
(transfer via smoke and heat).  However, corrosion and the potential for co=
rrosion of building components is readily assessable from visible inspectio=
n and reasonable testing.  For example, corrosion on mild steel or galvanis=
ed steel components and aluminium components (painted or unpainted) will ma=
nifest on exposed surfaces of those materials and are immediately apparent =
on visual inspection.  If no significant corrosion is present on surfaces d=
irectly exposed to heat and smoke, as was the situation observed in your cu=
stomers dwelling, enclosed surfaces such as within wall or ceiling cavities=
 will be less affected and therefore will not suffer corrosion from fire re=
lated fumes.  In all situations for remediation we consider the following s=
teps in order: cleaning; encapsulation (where cleaning alone is insufficien=
t and the product is not damaged or will not be damaged by cleaning); and r=
eplacement (where neither cleaning nor encapsulation will provide effective=
 remediation).  These steps also follow the same principles set out in the =
Institute of Inspection Cleaning, Restoration, and Certification (IICRC) co=
des of practice.
However, as your customer has provided new information regarding the possib=
le presence of pool chemicals, we suggest that we engage the services of Al=
exandra Dalzell from Forensic Specialists to undertake testing for the pres=
ence of residual chemicals on selected surfaces throughout the dwelling.  T=
he outcomes of such testing will then be used to further inform the remedia=
tion strategy and include, where appropriate, clearance testing post-repair.
Regarding structural matters, as this is a timber framed residential buildi=
ng and the structure can be addressed using the NZ Standard for timber fram=
ed buildings not requiring specific engineering design (NZS 3604:2011) ther=
e is no need for the involvement of a CPEng structural engineer.  Further, =
as one of the authors of NZS 3604 and current chair of that standards devel=
opment committee I provide ASURNZ with specialist timber and timber framing=
 knowledge that few engineers have, including regarding the durability of t=
imber and regulatory requirements that relate to the repair of existing bui=
ldings.  Also, the structural damage to timber members is readily apparent =
and relatively localised.  In this regard I do not believe there is any ben=
efit to be gained by engaging a CPEng structural engineer.

Regarding the provisions of s.112 of the Building Act 2004, these do not ap=
ply to the repair of this dwelling as none of the required building work re=
quires a building consent.  Similarly, the practice note from Auckland Coun=
cil does not apply, and in any case is not a regulatory or legislative requ=
irement.  Note that the defining legislation is the Building Act 2004 (the =
Act).  The Act overrides any policy of a building consent authority.  The p=
rovisions of the Act make clear that a building consent is not required for=
 the proposed repairs to this dwelling.

Regarding specific scope queries, I think is best to address these on site =
in the first instance.

Kind regards,

Stephen Walker
Principal Consultant

