<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"mso-line-height-alt:.75pt"><span style=3D"f=
ont-size:1.0pt;color:white">Any update, please? On 12 Sep 2025, at 5:</span=
><span style=3D"font-size:1.0pt;font-family:&quot;Arial&quot;,sans-serif;co=
lor:white">=E2=80=8A</span><span style=3D"font-size:1.0pt;color:white">37
 PM, raffaellanz@</span><span style=3D"font-size:1.0pt;font-family:&quot;Ar=
ial&quot;,sans-serif;color:white">=E2=80=8A</span><span style=3D"font-size:=
1.0pt;color:white">icloud.</span><span style=3D"font-size:1.0pt;font-family=
:&quot;Arial&quot;,sans-serif;color:white">=E2=80=8A</span><span style=3D"f=
ont-size:1.0pt;color:white">com
 wrote: Kia ora, Grant and Claim Maager/Team, Thank you for proposing to br=
ing the stakeholders together and provide a considered response. While I lo=
ok forward to receiving<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"mso-line-height-alt:.75pt"><span style=3D"f=
ont-size:1.0pt;color:white"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></span></p>
</div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal">Any update, please?<o:p></o:p></p>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"margin-bottom:12.0pt"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>
<blockquote style=3D"margin-top:5.0pt;margin-bottom:5.0pt">
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal">On 12 Sep 2025, at 5:37<span style=3D"font-family:&q=
uot;Arial&quot;,sans-serif">=E2=80=AF</span>PM,
<a href=3D"mailto:raffaellanz@icloud.com">raffaellanz@icloud.com</a> wrote:=
<o:p></o:p></p>
</div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><o:p>&nbsp;</o:p></p>
<div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt">Kia ora, Grant and =
Claim Maager/Team,<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt">Thank you for propo=
sing to bring the stakeholders together and provide a considered response. =
While I look forward to receiving written reply to my specific questions=E2=
=80=94could you please confirm when I=E2=80=99ll receive
 it and suggest a meeting date with an attendee list? &nbsp;To keep things =
professional and efficient, could we agree on clear deliverables and a test=
-led plan? To promote progress, I=E2=80=99m sharing my initial questions on=
 the documents received. I haven=E2=80=99t obtained professional
 advice yet, so I reserve the right to ask further questions, seek clarific=
ation, and provide additional feedback.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><u><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt">Fairness &amp; p=
articipation</span></u><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt"><br>
From the ASURNZ report there were two assessment sessions (11 and 21 August=
). I wasn=E2=80=99t invited to the briefings or either site inspection. I a=
ppreciate this may have been an oversight, but it leaves me without visibil=
ity of the brief given to ASURNZ and what
 they actually saw on the day.<br>
To balance the process, I kindly propose that Tower funds an independent in=
sured-side assessment with me directly engaged; and that I am permitted a o=
ne-on-one session with ASURNZ, as Grant had, so I can brief them directly a=
nd ask questions.<br>
I=E2=80=99d also be grateful for the raw site notes and photo log from thos=
e two attendances, and for inclusion (with reasonable notice) in all future=
 briefings, site visits, and communications.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><u><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt">Fire chemistry &=
amp; severity</span></u><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt"><br>
<span style=3D"color:#212121">FENZ records show spa-pool chlorine/oxidisers=
 stored in the origin cupboard, a HAZMAT requirement at dispatch, and escal=
ation to a second alarm; ASURNZ also records cavity smoke migration and roo=
f-edge heat (deformed soffit, melted
 gutter). Smoke odour remains three months later. Taken together, these fac=
tors indicate a heightened risk of corrosive/acidic residues and deep smoke=
 penetration into cavities, fixings, the roof assembly, and HVAC, so a visu=
al-only approach is not appropriate.</span><o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt;color:#212121">As su=
ch, could you please provide a written, insurer-funded plan and schedule se=
tting out methods/standards, pass criteria, dates, and named leads. The det=
ailed methodology and acceptance thresholds
 are to be designed and agreed by the appropriate independent experts (hygi=
enist, CPEng structural engineer, EWRB-licensed electrician/inspector, cert=
ifying gasfitter and HVAC technician, licensed plumber, and a moisture/corr=
osion specialist) and laboratories.
 &nbsp;Also it is my understanding that AC2213 (Auckland Council Fire Reins=
tatement practice note) expects intrusive investigation and formal sign-off=
s where the primary structure or external moisture/fire systems are affecte=
d, including removal of wet linings/insulation,
 a CPEng report on the impact to the primary structure, LBP design/supervis=
ion where applicable, and s.112 BA04 considerations.</span><span style=3D"f=
ont-size:10.0pt"><o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt;color:#212121">I als=
o believe that at a minimum&nbsp;the plan should address intrusive verifica=
tion of roof/eaves (including underlay, battens, fixings, and truss nail-pl=
ates, with perimeter residue/corrosivity
 checks where odour is present); cavity assessment on the first-floor south=
/west elevations and around the fireplace (with removal/cleaning and hygien=
ist clearance before re-lining where indicated); hygiene and clearance for =
heat-pump heads and the roof-space
 gas unit/any ducting; whole-installation electrical verification to AS/NZS=
 3000 with certification; plumbing system integrity testing and disinfectio=
n where indicated; moisture logging and corrosion/pH-chloride screening of =
representative framing/fasteners
 and masonry; and independent IAQ/surface clearances before re-lining and r=
e-occupation.</span><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt"><o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><u><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt">Scope adequacy</=
span></u><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt"><br>
From the ASURNZ document, there was smoke migration into first-floor caviti=
es with staining on the back of removed plasterboard, and roof-edge heat wi=
th deformed soffit sheeting and a melted gutter. The current scope appears =
focused on apparent damage (clean/smoke-seal,
 selective electrical checks, =E2=80=9Ctest &amp; recommission=E2=80=9D gas=
) rather than the real damage pathways (cavities, roof assembly, services, =
corrosion).<br>
Respectfully, it is not only the visibly charred beams that can be compromi=
sed. Non-charred structural members, fixings, nail-plates, and brick/mortar=
 exposed to smoke and/or acidic residues can degrade over time if not neutr=
alised or replaced.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<div>
<p class=3D"MsoNormal"><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt">Accordingly, could =
you please explain and evidence:<o:p></o:p></span></p>
</div>
<ul style=3D"margin-top:0in" type=3D"disc">
<li class=3D"MsoNormal" style=3D"mso-list:l14 level1 lfo1"><span style=3D"f=
ont-size:10.0pt">Why full removal of plasterboard/linings (GIB) in all area=
s showing cavity smoke migration is not proposed, given deep penetration an=
d potential chemical residues.<o:p></o:p></span></li><li class=3D"MsoNormal=
" style=3D"mso-list:l14 level1 lfo1"><span style=3D"font-size:10.0pt">The e=
vidence-based criteria being used to decide retain vs replace for framing, =
